Assuming the results turn out roughly according to the polls, I'm expecting long and complicated coalition negotiations and I'm quite certain the Greens will be in the new government, regardless how long it will take to form one. There is no way around the Greens unless the CDU/CSU distort themselves beyond recognition to be the minor partner in a coaltion with the SPD, so that gets a generous 4%. I think the Greens are going to be the Center of any negotiations and can get quite a lot of their demands, when they play Conserservatives and SPD against each other, especially when Greens and FDP quickly find a common ground. So the big unknowns at moment are: 1. What is the FDP doing? Because FDP and Union will get along pretty quickly and I asume also Union and Greens would (surprisingly quickly to most people) agree on most issues. That was already appearent four years ago, when the FDP all of a sudden withdraw from coaliton talks. I think in the end it will come down either Jamaica (Union-Green-FDP) or Red-Green-Red. Traffic light seems to me not likely the moment (although quite a lot of people would like to see that), especially when Greens and FDP not coming to a common ground at one point. If that results in a government, I'm not expecting that it will last for four years. I expect long and complicated talks between the parties but also within the parties, especially within the CDU (sorting out the post merkel future within the party), the FDP (party has been a Christian Lindner one man show the last four years), the Left (sticking to doctine and fundamentally to opposition or taking a more practical approach and seeking government responsibility).

I assume "no gov. will be formed ..." covers the (very plausible) case of negotiations still going on by 31.12. but no new election is called. As many three party coalition options will be possible negotiations are very likely to be prolonged. I say 60% chance of not being finished by 31.12. Case "Neither" would mean a coalition of SPD, Linke, FDP, AfD which is politically well nigh impossible. Case "Greens but not CDU/CSU" would mean coalition of SPD, Greens, FDP or SPD, Greens, Linke. Both would options would be possible if current polls would not change but both options would be politically difficult. I give them together 40% x (15%+10%)=10%. Case "CDU/CSU but not Greens" would mean coalition of CDU/CSU, SPD, FDP or CDU/CSU, SPD. I give them 40% x (20% + 7,5%)=11%

Guten Morgen @CJH, the Corona crisis plays no role at all in the german election. Climate, environment and justice are the issues. From a purely substantive point of view, a coalition of SPD-Greens-Left would fit together; at the moment, Germans most want a traffic light coalition of SPD-Greens-FDP. The FDP, however, would prefer a coalition with the CDU and the Greens. Recently, a coalition of SPD and CDU has also become possible again. The parties have now already announced exploratory talks after the elections for various combinations. I think these talks will take longer than before, I estimate up to four weeks. When it comes to coalition talks, for example, between the SPD, the Greens and the FDP, it could take a very long time because the Greens and the FDP sometimes have completely contradictory content. These talks could fail after 4-8 weeks. Then there are new specialization talks and coalition negotiations again - and all the sudden there is Christmas. Current example: Netherlands. There, the formation of a government has been ongoing for six months.

I continue my prediction that the Greens will be part of the next government by over 80%. I lowered my estimate of having the CDU in the government but not the Greens, because Armin Laschet announced, that the Conservatives would not join a government as a minor partner. However there might be still a slight chance, that the Conservatives will still join as a minor, because being in the opposition is also not a popular option for many of them. I increase the chance of having no government at the end of 2021. At the moment there seems five (more of less) viable constellations of forming a government, but all of them require three parties, which would make negotiations, with plenty of bitter pills to swallow plus the approvals by all the involved party bases much more complicated and time consuming. And in case of failure this all starts all over again.

In the last poll, the SPD is 5% ahead of the CDU: https://www.wahlrecht.de/umfragen/insa.htm Nevertheless, given the voter potential, it is likely that the CDU will catch up again by election day at the latest. It is very likely that it will be very close between the CDU and SPD and that there will be many coalition variants. Therefore, the probability has become high that there will be more than one coalition negotiation as in 2017. If the CDU becomes the strongest force, it will start the talks, but they may fail if the Greens drop out and continue negotiating with SPD and Left or FDP. So there is a realistic chance that no new federal government will be sworn in this year. In the last federal election on September 24, 2017, the first coalition negotiations failed and after a total of 5 months and 5 days, the new government was sworn in.

The candidates of both CDU and Greens doing not so well, after the floods in the West of Germany, the Taliban takeover in Afghanistan and most of all both of them are perceived of lacking integrity for different reasons. So the SPD and their candidate are doing relatively well, which gives them a not unrealistic chance of actually forming a coalition. At the moment it looks like there will be several viable options of forming a government unlike after the last election, when nobody was really happy with the result. For me it comes down to the question: How likely is it, that the Greens will be part of the next government. I think the probability of the Greens joining the government is at least 80%. Why? Because they are hungry for power after 16 years of opposition. The CDU sees itself as the "naturaly rightful" ruling party. Additionally the CDU moved under Angela Merkel considerably away from many classic conservative positions. So not unreasonable to assume them both in the next government and actually getting along quite well with each other. This why I see CDU and Greens over 50% in the next government, but also for the Greens having realistically also options cooperating with other parties.

I changed a bit the probabilities of my last forecast. I lowered the probability of having no government formed until end of the year. I do that because Germans don't like uncertainty and adding to that, long negotiations of a new coalition only benefit the AfD, so rather continuing such an unease, someone is going to swallow some bitter pills. My take for the moment is Greens and the Union, if they get enough seats together. The Greens because they are eager to get into power, and in their mindset, they have been way to long in the opposition. The Union on the other hand probably going to have some heated dicussions about joining in or leading the opposition, similar to the SPD four years ago. But to be a junior in government is a rather foreign thought to them, which they first have to get used to. When numbers are so, that a government can't formed without the Union, they are grudgingly joining, cause avoiding uncertainty, but not without some turmoil within the party. I increased the probability that Union will be in the government but not the Greens and decreasing government with the Greens but now Union. I do that, cause there is, in my estimate, the hype the Greens got from nominating their chanceller candidate is going to dampen a bit, while the Union after the more chaotic nomination is closing their ranks.
The greens will get the majority of votes, the CDU being the junior partner. Candidates of the greens appeal much mote to the majority of younger voters- they will decide the election.

Greens: SPD, Linke, Union, FDP Greens, SPD and Linke would probably fall short of a majority and FDP would probably not join such a coalition again increasing the odds of a Green-Union government.

At the moment, I think, it's most likely both Greens and CDU will be in the new government. Mainly because, a government with only one of them, would be quite unstable (if at all possible), because of just a tiny majority in a multiparty coalition covering a relatively wide political spectrum. The question is: Do they have a majority together? If yes, they will quickly get an agreement and form the new government. They had already talks after the last election together with the FDP. This talks actually went, to the surprise of a lot of observers, well between Greens and CDU/CSU, but failed in end because the FDP pulled suddenly out. So Greens and CDU would go along quite well with each other. The other possiblity is they are going to need a third partner and this might be tricky to get an agreement there until end of 2021. This would not be unpresented as I just described. AfD would be not an option for both of them, the Left party almost certainly would be a no go for CDU/CSU, so the only viable options would be FDP and Social Democrats, the first would consider the government option more seriously than four years ago and Social Democrats, I asume, pretty much split about a government role, where they can have an influence but crumble even more or going into the opposition and hoping to sharpen the party profile the next years.

There are only limited indications that the CDU faces the prospects of diminished electoral victories. The Green Party could be squeezed out of government if the CDU decides to form another grand coalition with the SPD with a combined majority or find another partner(s). The prospects of the SPD in generally appears to be stagnant with the slight possibility of picking up a couple of seats, but equally possible of losing seats. The differences between the CDU and SPD, while at times can be stark, in general under Merkel has been closer ideologically, The SPD simply does not have enough coalition options to form a government, barring a major shake up in the election. It is highly likely that the CDU and SPD will form another government with other partners, but the SPD may attempt to press for the formation of their own government or, more likely, press for concession from the CDU before entering into a grand coalition that may push the formation of a government into 2022.

Honored that my question suggestion is live now at GJ Open, and I am now under pressure to make a forecast ;-). First, the easy part: Yes, it took forever last time for a coalition to form. This year we there is a pandemic; as opposed to the relatively uneventful winter of 2017/18, Germans would not accept coalition negotiations stretching into the next year. Remains the tricky part of predicting who will build a coalition in 2021. A very helpful (German language) page is https://www.bundestagswahl-2021.de/koalitionen/ ; you can see that none of the actual coalitions of the past have a shot at a majority in the Bundestag, even CDU/CSU+SPD might, for the first time in history, not reach half of the seats together. CDU/CSU will be, despite their internal conflict, almost for sure be the strongest party and try to form a coalition. The Greens will be, almost for sure, number two. If CDU/CSU+Greens reach a majority, it is likely they overcome their differences and form a coalition (like in Austria, where this coalition formed even before Corona). If CDU/CSU+Greens don’t reach a majority, they will try again to form a “Jamaica” coalition together with the FDP; as the FDP, after leaving the Jamaica talks in 17/18, subsequently lost heavily in support, they will be inclined to join this time (plus the pressure taking responsibility due the health crisis). All other options are pretty unlikely: The “Kenia” variant with CDU/CSU+Greens+SPD will be pretty oversized (therefore unlikely, see Axelrod’s minimal connected winning coalition theorem: https%3A%2F%2Flirias.kuleuven.be%2Fretrieve%2F280402&usg=AOvVaw0fZrpEqCKRUWhhRk47r9KR ) The “Germany” CDU/CSU+SPD+FDP would be novel, and very surprising outcome, as there are be even more differences to overcome. All in all, - very unlikely no coalition this year - very unlikely neither CDU nor Greens in it - very likely both of them are part of it
